0.2 Running a Basic Model on Combigen¶

In this notebook we’re going to just run the combigen task designed in nb 0.1 on the simple model used in the paper.

Boilerplate¶

The following subsections are largely boilerplate code, so skip around as needed.

The Combigen Task¶

Now that the task has been put together from nb 0.1 (and fixed several times, see nb-0.1.x), let’s import the functionified version of it and start prepping for running the model.

First let’s refresh our memory on the task.

[10]:

cgh.visualize_combigen(5)
plt.show()

Now that it works as expected, lets move back to setting up the data.

O’Reily BP Models¶

Before working with anything close to state of the art (SOTA), a good place to start is with the backpropagation model that O’Reily used in his paper.

First, let’s create the training and testing data that will be used.

[47]:

# Data parameters
stack = 4
size = 5
dims = 2

# Training Data
training_n = 100
training_y = cg.generate_labels(n_samples=training_n, stack=stack, size=size, dims=dims)
training_x = cg.inverse_transform(training_y)
# Testing data
testing_n = 500
testing_y = cg.generate_labels(n_samples=testing_n, stack=stack, size=size, dims=dims)
testing_x = cg.inverse_transform(testing_y)

print('Training X shape: {0}. Training y shape: {1}'.format(training_x.shape, training_y.shape))
print('Testing X shape: {0}. Testing y shape: {1}'.format(testing_x.shape, testing_y.shape))

Training X shape: (100, 4, 5, 5). Training y shape: (100, 4, 5, 2)
Testing X shape: (500, 4, 5, 5). Testing y shape: (500, 4, 5, 2)

First Pass Implementation¶

Now let’s build the O’Reily BP model. It’s described as a fully connected network with 100 hidden units and trained with 500 epochs.

[49]:

def bp_model(hidden_units=100, stack=4, size=5, dims=2):
    """Builds and returns the model"""
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Reshape((stack*size*size,), name='Initial_reshape'))
    # Single hidden layer
    model.add(layers.Dense(hidden_units, activation='sigmoid', name='Hidden_Layer'))
    # Output layer
    model.add(layers.Dense(stack*size*dims, activation='sigmoid', name='Output_Layer'))
    # Reshape to match the labels
    model.add(layers.Reshape((stack, size, dims), name='Output_reshape'))

    model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop',
                  loss='mse',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

model = bp_model()
model.fit(training_x, training_y, epochs=500, batch_size=1, verbose=0, callbacks=[TQDMNotebookCallback()])
model.summary()

score = model.evaluate(testing_x, testing_y, batch_size=1)
print('Loss and accuracy:', score)

And then to get a sence of how it’s performing on the tasks specifically, let’s run the model on some data and visualize it.

example_y = cg.generate_labels()

pred_y = model.predict(example_x)
cgh.heatmap(pred_y)
cgh.heatmap(example_y)
plt.show()

Tanh Hidden and Output Layers¶

The model above was run on using sigmoid functions, let’s see if there is any performance difference when using tanh functions.

[54]:

def bp_model_tanh(hidden_units=100, stack=4, size=5, dims=2):
    """Builds and returns the model"""
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Reshape((stack*size*size,), name='Initial_reshape'))
    # Single hidden layer
    model.add(layers.Dense(hidden_units, activation='tanh', name='Hidden_Layer'))
    # Output layer
    model.add(layers.Dense(stack*size*dims, activation='tanh', name='Output_Layer'))
    # Reshape to match the labels
    model.add(layers.Reshape((stack, size, dims), name='Output_reshape'))

    model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop',
                  loss='mse',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

model = bp_model_tanh()
model.fit(training_x, training_y, epochs=500, batch_size=1, verbose=0, callbacks=[TQDMNotebookCallback()])
model.summary()

score = model.evaluate(testing_x, testing_y, batch_size=1)
print('Loss and accuracy:', score)

example_y = cg.generate_labels()
example_x = cg.inverse_transform(example_y)
pred_y = model.predict(example_x)
cgh.heatmap(pred_y)
cgh.heatmap(example_y)
plt.show()

Sigmoid Hidden Layer and Linear Output Layer¶

One last thing to try with the architecture would be to see how it performs with just a linear output layer.

[55]:

def bp_model_sig_lin(hidden_units=100, stack=4, size=5, dims=2):
    """Builds and returns the model"""
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Reshape((stack*size*size,), name='Initial_reshape'))
    # Single hidden layer
    model.add(layers.Dense(hidden_units, activation='sigmoid', name='Hidden_Layer'))
    # Output layer
    model.add(layers.Dense(stack*size*dims, activation=None, name='Output_Layer'))
    # Reshape to match the labels
    model.add(layers.Reshape((stack, size, dims), name='Output_reshape'))

    model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop',
                  loss='mse',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

model = bp_model_sig_lin()
model.fit(training_x, training_y, epochs=500, batch_size=1, verbose=0, callbacks=[TQDMNotebookCallback()])
model.summary()

score = model.evaluate(testing_x, testing_y, batch_size=1)
print('Loss and accuracy:', score)

example_y = cg.generate_labels()
example_x = cg.inverse_transform(example_y)
pred_y = model.predict(example_x)
cgh.heatmap(pred_y)
cgh.heatmap(example_y)
plt.show()

Effects of Training Set Size¶

O’Reily used a training set of 100 samples and a test set of 500. How does the accuracy of the model change as a function of training samples?

[58]:

score = []
training_set_sizes = [25, 50, 100, 200, 400]
for training_set_n in tqdm(training_set_sizes):
    training_set_y = cg.generate_labels(n_samples=training_set_n, stack=stack, size=size, dims=dims)
    training_set_x = cg.inverse_transform(training_set_y)
    model = bp_model_sig_lin()
    model.fit(training_x, training_y, epochs=500, batch_size=1, verbose=0, callbacks=[TQDMNotebookCallback()])
    score.append(model.evaluate(testing_x, testing_y, batch_size=1))

This produced a list of lists containing the loss and the accuracy. Let’s unpack it and plot each of them.

[71]:

loss, accuracy = list(map(list, zip(*score)))

plt.plot(training_set_sizes, loss, marker='o')
plt.title('Loss vs Training Set Size')
plt.show()
plt.plot(training_set_sizes, accuracy, marker='o')
plt.title('Accuracy vs Training Set Size')
plt.show()

The accuracy and loss don’t change much but this is likely due to the loss function not being entirely appropriate for the task.
